ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescence spectroscopy has been used to investigate the sensing potential of fluorescent materials. It is one of the most recent, facile, fast and more sensitive methods to explore sensing applications. Here we use fluorescent spectroscopy to examine the potential capability of N,S-CDs as metal sensing agents. Various metals ions of concentration of 5 mM are introduced to N,S-CDs solutions such as (Pb2+, Cu2+, Co2+, Hg2+, Cr3+, Sr2+, Mn2+, Sn2+, Fe2+, Fe3+, Cd2+, Ni2+) for possible application. Among all metal ions studied, Hg2+ ions are found to quench the PL intensity of N,S-CDs intensively, as shown in Fig. 4
                        a. The photographs in Fig. 4b show pure N,S-CDs on the left side-emitting bright blue light. In contrast, the right side photograph with Hg2+ ions is dark under the same conditions, indicating that the fluorescence of N,S-CDs has been quenched by adding toxic Hg2+ ions. We further investigated the potential capability of obtained N,S-CDs for quantitatively detecting Hg2+ ions. PL emission intensity of the produced N,S-CDs falls monotonically as the concentration of Hg2+ increases (Fig. 4c), suggesting that adding Hg2+ ions effectively quenches the luminescence of the N,S-CDs. Fig. 4d presents the emission intensity under different concentrations of Hg2+ ions. Fluorescent N,S-CDs can detect Hg2+ ions at a concentration as low as 3.5 nM using 3 times δ/K ratio, and a good linear correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.985) is exhibited over the concentration range of (0～100) nM. The detection limit of this N,S-CDs is much lower than those of the previously reported CDs (Table 1
                        ). The observed results confirmed that prepared N,S-CDs are very sensitive toward Hg2+ using the fluorescent spectroscopy technique. In addition, fluorescent N,S-CDs could be used as a chemical sensor for Hg2+ detection in real water and milk samples.
